eanings":[{"name":"Achard,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Hatchard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatchard","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Acard</i>, <i>Achart</i>, <i>Echard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Agihard</i>, from <i>agi</i> ‘point, edge (of a sword)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave’. The initial <i>H-</i> is prosthetic."]},{"name":"Ackert","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Acard</i>, <i>Achart</i>, <i>Aquart</i>, a derivative of an ancient Germanic personal name <i>Agihard</i>, <i>Akihart</i>, which is composed of the elements <i>agi(n)</i> ‘edge (of a sword)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name (with the same etymology as 1); compare   Eckert  .","Americanized form of German   Eckert  , a cognate of the names above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Achard, II was born about 1160, in Aldermaston, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Achard, was 36 and his mother, Beatrice Rumenel, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Achard. He died in 1217, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"ca. 1160–1217":"umbes 1160–1217","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–Female":"Surnud","1200–1241":"1200–1241","1125–1167":"1125–1167","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1217":"1217","ca. 1160":"umbes 1160","1125":"1125","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","ca. 1200":"umbes 1200","1241":"1241","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Aldermaston, Berkshire, England":"Aldermaston, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ca. 1160–1217":"noin 1160–1217","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–Female":"Kuollut","1200–1241":"1200–1241","1125–1167":"1125–1167","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1217":"1217","ca. 1160":"noin 1160","1125":"1125","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","ca. 1200":"noin 1200","1241":"1241","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Aldermaston, Berkshire, England":"Aldermaston, Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ca. 1160–1217":"environ 1160–1217","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–Female":"Décédée","1200–1241":"1200–1241","1125–1167":"1125–1167","1130–Female":"1130–Décédée","1217":"1217","ca. 1160":"environ 1160","1125":"1125","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","ca. 1200":"environ 1200","1241":"1241","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Aldermaston, Berkshire, England":"Aldermaston, Berkshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Achard, II est né environ 1160, à Aldermaston, Berkshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William Achard, avait 36 ans et sa mère, Beatrice Rumenel, avait 31 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Margaret Achard. Il est décédé en 1217, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 58 ans."},"de":{"ca. 1160–1217":"um 1160–1217","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–Female":"Verstorben","1200–1241":"1200–1241","1125–1167":"1125–1167","1130–Female":"1130–Verstorben","1217":"1217","ca. 1160":"um 1160","1125":"1125","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","ca. 1200":"um 1200","1241":"1241","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","Aldermaston, Berkshire, England":"Aldermaston, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Als William Achard, II um 1160 in Aldermaston, 